						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="170r" to="237v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">ʻEn ha-kore</title>
							<title xml:lang="he">עין הקורא</title>
							<author>
								<persName xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Yeḳutiʼel ben Yitsḥaḳ Naḳdan</persName>
								<persName xml:lang="he">יקותיאל בן יצחק נקדן</persName>
							</author>
							<note>
								<p>A grammatico-masoretic treatise on the Pentateuch, Esther and Lamentations.</p>
							</note>
							<incipit xml:lang="he">ברוך יי' אלהי ישראל אשר נתן למשרתו יקותיאל עין רואה ואזן שומעת' לשון למודים לדעת' לעשות עבדת מלאכת הקדש' ודברים עתיקים לחדש'.</incipit>
							<filiation>
								<ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">968</ref>
							</filiation>
							<textLang mainLang="he"/>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="v">
							<locus from="237v" to="252v"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">A collection of several pieces on masorah, punctuation and accents.</title>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Parchment codex of the 14th century.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="perg">
								<support>Parchment codex.</support>
								<extent rend="visible">252 folios<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>290</height>
										<width>215</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>180</height>
										<width>135</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>252 folios (+3 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end). </p>
									<p>Foliation in pencil can be found also in the outer lower corner of recto sides, hardly visible.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>32 quires of mostly 8 leaves, apart from two consisting of 6 leaves. </p>
									<p>Vertical catchwords at the end of quires, decorated. </p>
								</collation>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="2" ruledLines="33" writtenLines="32">
									<p>Uniform layout. </p>
									<p>Double pricking for major lines, in outer and inner margins, quire by quire. </p>
									<p>Complete ruling by plummet (each bifolium on both sides). </p>
									<p>Last written line within ruling. </p>
									<p>Graphic filler at the end of line. </p>
									<p>Masorah magna often written in the form of figures, animals and patterns; otherwise it occupies three lines in the upper margin and two in the lower margin.</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="3">
							<summary>Ashkenazi square and semi-cursive script of the 13th century; punctuation provided by two different hands. R. <name type="person" role="scribe">Simḥah bar Shemu᾿el ha-Levi</name>: mentioned in the colophon at the end of the Pentateuch, Monday 21, Adar Sheni, 1395, folio 169v; also mentioned as scribe in the colophon at the end of the codex, Coburg, 1396, folio 252r; the word שמחה is decorated several times (e.g. 17v, 112v, 126v, 131v, 132r, 154v, 184v). </summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="major">
								<p>
									<persName role="scribe">Simhah ben Samuel ha-Levi</persName> - scribe, <persName>Samuel ben Abraham of Molerstadt</persName> - punctuator of the Pentateuch, <persName>Gershom ben Judah</persName> - punctuator of the rest of the codex.</p>
							</handNote>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>Written by </p>
							<p>The Pentateuch was punctuated by R. Samuel bar Abraham of Molerstadt : mentioned in a marginal note as the punctuator (folio 96r); inscribed with his name in a colophon as the punctuator who punctuated the codex &apos;until this point&apos; within six weeks, Sunday, beginning of Kislev, folio 112v; mentioned as punctuator of the Pentateuch who punctuated it in Babenberg, colophon at the end of the codex, dated 1396, folio 252r.</p>
							<p>The Five Scrolls, the Haftarot and the grammatical treatise were punctuated by R.Gershom bar Judah in Rödelsee, colophon at the end of the codex, dated 1396, folio 252r. </p>
							<p>Obituary entries: death of a later owner&apos;s parents (Bittingen, 1535, and Wallerstein, 1539) (folio 252r).</p>
							<p>
								<name type="person" role="owner">Alexander ben Solomon Zalman Kohen</name>: inscribed with his name, 1750, folio 1r. </p>
							<p>Illegible Hebrew inscriptions, folio 1r.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Dark brown leather. </p>
								<p>Spine: &apos;Pentateuch. Hebrew. Brit. Mus. Additional 19,776.&apos;</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
